<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-966-016  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 966 016.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 11 1989 v6 n49 p43(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>OptionFinder 3.1 aims to bolster productivity of corporatemeetings. (Option Technologies)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Higgins, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Option Technologies' $8,995 OptionFinder 3.1 is a polling anddata-presentation package aimed at streamlining corporate meetingsthrough sophisticated data manipulation, automated polling andimmediate posting of results.andP;  Corporations using OptionFinderfind its results are more precise than that taken fromun-automated meetings mainly because OptionFinder ensures thateveryone participates.andP;  A typical use of the program would be topoll members of a meeting on the relative importance of up toeight goals shown on a presentation screen.andP;  The attendees use akeypad to choose the most important goal and the softwaretabulates the results and offers results in graphical or textform.andP;  OptionFinder requires an 80286-based microcomputer with a20Mbyte hard disk and 640Kbytes RAM.andP;  The keypads cost $105 eachand the LCD projection panel costs $1,119.andP;  Upgrades from previousversions are free.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Option Technologies Inc. (products).andO;Topic:     Presentation SoftwareUser SurveyConferences and MeetingsAutomation.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Benefits Option Technologies' OptionFinder can provide. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steve HigginsandM;While a growing number of companies are using PCs to improve the productivityof dispersed work groups, a Minnesota firm is using PC technology to boostproductivity among people working face-to-face.andM;Taking aim at time-consuming, ineffective corporate meetings, OptionTechnologies recently released OptionFinder version 3.1, an upgrade to itsDOS-based polling and data-presentation software that adds sophisticateddata-manipulation features and support for IBM's PS/2 Model 80.andP;  OptionFinderworks with a presentation screen and Option Technologies' keypads, which canbe daisy-chained to a PC's serial port to serve as a communications vehiclefor as many as 120 people, according to officials at the Mendota Heights,Minn., firm.andM;The package reduces the time necessary to reach a consensus in meetings bystreamlining the polling process and posting results moments later, either onthe PC or a presentation screen, users said.andP;  The resulting data, which istabulated according to preset parameters and presented in graphical or textform, is more precise than data culled from more informal meetings because itensures that all attendees participate, they said.andM;KCA Research, a research firm in Sacramento, Calif., uses OptionFinder in theplanning meetings it sponsors for organizations.andP;  OptionFinder's &quot;pairedcomparison&quot; feature, for example, enables KCA to poll organization members onthe comparative importance of as many as eight goals.andP;  Respondents are showntwo goals on-screen and use keypads to choose the more important one.andP;  Thesoftware tabulates the results and ranks the goals.andP;  &quot;It forces everyone inthe group to have an opinion,&quot; said Lynne Cunningham, vice president of KCA.andM;Moore Business Corp., a Glenview, Ill., forms manufacturer, uses OptionFinderto pinpoint its sales forces' weak areas and thus determine topics fortraining.andM;&quot;OptionFinder lets us determine what needs to be taught quicker, faster andbetter&quot; than could a manual polling system, said Gary Hultgren, the firm'sdirector of sales training.andM;The $8,995 OptionFinder version 3.1 works on 286-based PCs with 20M-byte harddisks and 640K bytes of RAM.andP;  The keypads cost $105 each, and an LCD panelused to project results onto a screen costs $1,119.andP;  Current users canupgrade for free.andM;Option Technologies can be reached at (612) 450-1700.andO;</TEXT></DOC>